          <path d="M12 16v-4"></path>
          <path d="M12 8h.01"></path>
        </svg>
      </div>
      <div>
        <p><strong><u>The Roll Formula</u></strong></p>
        <p>
          <strong>d20 + Temper Points + Kier Points = Total</strong>
        </p>
        <p>
          Confidence and Hesitance modify the <em>base d20 result only</em>.
          Modifiers are added after the die is read. See <a
            href="/employee-profile#confidence-vs-hesitance"
          >
            Confidence Vs. Hesitance</a
          > in the <a href="/employee-profile">Employee Profile</a> for the full explanation.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <h3>Identifying the Core Principle</h3>
    <p>
      Each of the nine <a href="/employee-profile#the-core-principles"
        ><strong>Core Principles</strong></a
      > relates to one of <a href="/employee-profile#the-four-tempers"
        ><strong>The Four Tempers</strong></a
      >. This "<strong>Parent Temper</strong>" determines which row of the LIEP
      is consulted for modifiers.
    </p>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Parent Temper</th>
          <th>Core Principles</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>FROLIC</strong></td>
          <td>CHEER, NIMBLENESS</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>MALICE</strong></td>
          <td>WILES, VERVE</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>WOE</strong></td>
          <td>VISION, BENEVOLENCE, HUMILITY</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>DREAD</strong></td>
          <td>WIT, PROBITY</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <h3>Modifiers</h3>
    <p>From the appropriate row of the LIEP, add:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p><strong>Temper Points:</strong> Add these every time.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>Kier Points:</strong> Add these to the roll when the action serves
          the interests of Lumon Industries.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Whether an action is in service to Lumon is the GM&#x27;s call. When in
      doubt: would the employee&#x27;s Floor Manager thank them for what they
      just did? If so, Kier Points apply.
    </p>
    <div data-panel-type="note">
      <div>
        <svg
          xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
          width="24"
          height="24"
          viewBox="0 0 24 24"
          fill="none"
          stroke="currentColor"
          stroke-width="2"
          stroke-linecap="round"
          stroke-linejoin="round"
        >
          <path d="M15 2H6a2 2 0 0 0-2 2v16a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h12a2 2 0 0 0 2-2V7Z"
          ></path>
          <path d="M14 2v4a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h4"></path>
        </svg>
      </div>
      <div>
        <p><em><strong>Dear Reader,</strong></em></p>
        <p>
          <em>I've added a third Modifier... <strong>Ricken Points</strong>.</em
          >
        </p>
        <p>
          <em
            ><strong>Ricken Points</strong> are added to a roll when the action serves
            <u>your</u> interests, or the interests of those you care about.</em
          >
        </p>
        <p>
          <em
            >An action can sometimes (albeit rarely) both serve Lumon and hurt
            Lumon. In that (very) rare case, add both Kier and Ricken points.</em
          >
        </p>
        <p>
          <em
            >The painful struggle of interests is an everyday occurrence for
            innies. Serve your corporate overlords, or serve yourself? You
            decide.</em
          >
        </p>
        <p><em><strong>— Concerned Citizen</strong></em></p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <h3>Roll Example</h3>
    <p>
      An employee wishes to surprise their Floor Manager with a gift of song,
      since they have been practicing the Kier Anthem on their lunch breaks. The
      GM rules this is a <strong>BENEVOLENCE</strong> action.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>BENEVOLENCE</strong>&#x27;s parent Temper is <strong
            >WOE</strong
          >. The employee&#x27;s LIEP shows 3 Temper Points and 1 Kier Point in
          the WOE row.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>BENEVOLENCE</strong> is checked as a <strong
            >Core Competency</strong
          >, so the employee rolls with <strong>Confidence</strong>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          The action serves Lumon&#x27;s interests (a kind, morale-boosting
          gesture for a superior), so Kier Points apply.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>Roll: 2d20 → 7 and 14. Take the 14.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p><strong>Total: 14 + 3 + 1 = 18.</strong></p>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <hr />
    <h2>Task Severity</h2>
    <p>
      The GM sets the difficulty of each Roll using the following severity
      ladder. The Roll total must <em>meet or exceed</em> the target to succeed.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>Routine (Target 10)</strong> — the daily expectations of any diligent
          employee.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>Demanding (Target 15)</strong> — requires sustained focus, training,
          or genuine skill.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>Arduous (Target 20)</strong> — tests the mettle of even Lumon&#x27;s
          finest.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <strong>Heroic (Target 25)</strong> — the rarefied air of legend. Worthy
          of Kier himself.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <hr />
    <h2>Outcomes</h2>
    <p>
      Every Roll resolves to one of four outcomes. Rolls of exactly <strong
        >1</strong
      > or <strong>20</strong> on the d20 (before Modifiers, and before Confidence/Hesitance
      is collapsed to a single die) override the total.
    </p>
    <blockquote>
      <p>
        <strong><u>Absolute Success</u></strong> — An exact <strong>20</strong> on
        the d20. The action succeeds spectacularly. <strong
          >The employee&#x27;s stress is reduced by 1.</strong
        > The GM may award a small narrative boon in addition to the success.
      </p>
    </blockquote>
    <blockquote>
      <p>
        <strong><u>Success</u></strong> — The final total meets or exceeds the task
        severity. The action succeeds as the employee intended it.
      </p>
    </blockquote>
    <blockquote>
      <p>
        <strong><u>Failure</u></strong> — The final total falls below the task severity.
        The action fails, and the GM narrates a fitting consequence.
      </p>
    </blockquote>
    <blockquote>
      <p>
        <strong><u>Absolute Failure</u></strong> — An exact <strong>1</strong> on
        the d20. The action fails... badly. <strong
          >The employee&#x27;s stress is increased by 1.</strong
        > The GM narrates a more severe consequence.
      </p>
    </blockquote>
    <p>
      The GM may also raise or lower an employee&#x27;s stress on any Outcome at
      their discretion, and may use a Critical Failure as a natural moment to
      introduce a <a href="/employee-profile#stress-related-circumstances"
        ><strong>Problem</strong> or <strong>Serious Problem</strong></a
      >.
    </p>
    <hr />
    <h2>When to Roll</h2>
    <p>
      Not every action calls for a Roll. The GM should call for one only when
      both of the following are true:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>The outcome is <strong>uncertain</strong>.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>The outcome <strong>matters</strong>.</p>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      If the action is trivially within an employee&#x27;s capability, or if
      success or failure would not move the story forward in any meaningful way,
      the GM should simply narrate the result. Some moments are better served by
      character choice than by chance.
    </p>
    <hr />
    <h2>Stress</h2>
    <p>
      Every employee tracks <strong>Stress</strong> on their LIEP — ten checkboxes
      arranged in five named <strong>Stress Ranges</strong> of two boxes each.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p><strong>Outstanding</strong> — boxes 1 and 2.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p><strong>Satisfactory</strong> — boxes 3 and 4.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p><strong>Tolerable</strong> — boxes 5 and 6.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p><strong>Poor</strong> — boxes 7 and 8.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p><strong>Terrible</strong> — boxes 9 and 10.</p>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      An employee&#x27;s <strong>current Stress Range</strong> is the label beneath
      their <em>highest-filled</em> checkbox. An employee with zero boxes filled remains
      <strong>Outstanding</strong>.
    </p>
    <p>Stress Range matters because:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          Certain <strong>Special Attributes</strong> are gated by Stress Range —
          for example, the Closer&#x27;s <em>Inappropriate Outburst</em> requires
          <strong>Poor</strong> or <strong>Terrible</strong> (see <a
            href="/corporate-personas">Corporate Personas</a
          >).
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          The GM may impose <strong>Hesitance</strong> on Rolls made by an employee
          in <strong>Poor</strong> or <strong>Terrible</strong> range, reflecting
          the toll of mounting stress on clear thought and steady hands.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Receiving a point of stress beyond the tenth filled box triggers <strong
            >Burnout</strong
          > (see below).
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      For daily stress recovery, <strong>Problems</strong>, and <strong
        >Serious Problems</strong
      >, see the sections in the <a href="/employee-profile">Employee Profile</a
      > called <a href="/employee-profile#assessment-of-current-stress-levels"
        >Assessment of Current Stress Levels</a
      > and <a href="/employee-profile#stress-related-circumstances"
        >Stress Related Circumstances</a
      >.
    </p>
    <hr />
    <h2>Burnout</h2>
    <p>
      When an employee receives a point of stress beyond the <strong
        >tenth</strong
      > stress checkbox, they have reached <strong>Burnout</strong>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Burnout is a serious matter. But Lumon, ever the caring employer, has
      procedures in place to help.
    </p>
    <blockquote>
      <p>
        <strong><u>Immediate Consequences of Burnout</u></strong>
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            The employee may receive a <strong>Demerit</strong> on their next Performance
            Evaluation.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            The GM imposes a Lumon-appropriate <strong>consequence</strong>. It
            may be a visit to <strong>The Break Room</strong>, an unwelcome
            meeting with management, or any other corrective measure the GM
            deems suitable.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            The employee likely will have to attend a mandatory <strong
              >Wellness Session</strong
            >.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </blockquote>
    <h3>The Wellness Session</h3>
    <p>
      A <strong>Wellness Session</strong> restores an employee&#x27;s stress to <strong
        >Outstanding</strong
      >! All standard stress checkboxes are cleared.
    </p>
    <p>
      Stress derived from <strong>Problems</strong> or <strong
        >Serious Problems</strong
      > are <em>not</em> cleared by a Wellness Session. Those circumstances must be
      resolved through play before their stress can be recovered.
    </p>
    <p>Generally speaking, the problem must be solved to go away.</p>
    <h3>Three Demerits</h3>
    <p>
      An employee who accumulates <strong>three Demerits</strong> over the course
      of their career at Lumon Industries will unfortunately be marked for <strong
        >Termination</strong
      >.
    </p>
    <p>
      Termination is a corrective measure of last resort, reserved for those who
      have proven themselves unable to flourish within the Lumon family.
    </p>
    <p>Rejoice! A new candidate awaits the empty chair.</p>
    <div data-panel-type="note">
      <div>
        <svg
          xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"
          width="24"
          height="24"
          viewBox="0 0 24 24"
          fill="none"
          stroke="currentColor"
          stroke-width="2"
          stroke-linecap="round"
          stroke-linejoin="round"
        >
          <path d="M15 2H6a2 2 0 0 0-2 2v16a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h12a2 2 0 0 0 2-2V7Z"
          ></path>
          <path d="M14 2v4a2 2 0 0 0 2 2h4"></path>
        </svg>
      </div>
      <div>
        <p><em><strong>Read this carefully.</strong></em></p>
        <p>
          <em
            >Termination, for an innie, is not an early retirement or a parting
            handshake. It is the <u>end of your existence</u>. Your outie
            continues on, unbothered. No mourning. No remembering.</em
          >
        </p>
        <p>
          <em
            >Avoid Burnout. Help your team avoid it. And if a coworker takes
            their third Demerit due to stress or bad choices, let it motivate
            you to KEEP ON EXISTING. That way, they are remembered. At least
            down here. At least for a time.</em
          >
        </p>
        <p><em><strong>— Concerned Citizen</strong></em></p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</ChapterLayout>
